				"string" : "---\n\n# ✔ Implicit Structural Themes (very relevant for curriculum design)\n\nThese appear across the notes and should become formal structural categories:\n\n### A. **Main Path vs Side Roads**\n\nMain path = Minimal conceptual backbone for Newcomers\nSide roads = Explorations:\n\n* Mondrian\n* Sceneries\n* Language Workbenches\n* Inspector coding pattern\n* Topic Maps\n* Roadmaps\n* Domain modelling patterns\n  → These become *optional chapters*.\n\n### B. **Navigation Metaphors**\n\n* Accordion (micro-cycle)\n* Roadmaps (macro-structure)\n* Trees / branches (Learning Units)\n* Sceneries (auto-generated learning flow)\n* Topic Maps (semantic linking)\n  → All four need unified terminology.\n\n### C. **Generated Visual Maps**\n\n* Sceneries for Learning Unit maps\n* Mondrian views for structure exploration\n* Roadmaps for high-level navigation\n\n### D. **Beginner Orientation**\n\nWhat must a newcomer learn:\n\n1. GT mental model\n2. Navigation in GT\n3. Domain model creation\n4. Contextual tools & views\n5. Examples & playgrounds\n6. Side roads\n\n---\n\n# ✔ Recommended Next Steps (focused + minimal friction)\n\n## **Step 1 — Formalize Learning Unit 1 as a Tree**\n\nCreate:\n\n**Learning Unit 1**\n\n* *Main Path*:\n\n  1. What is GT?\n  2. Inspecting objects\n  3. Playgrounds\n  4. Domain modelling basics\n  5. Creating first views\n  6. Using examples\n\n* *Side Roads*:\n\n  * Mondrian basics\n  * Sceneries basics\n  * Topic Maps basics\n  * Accordion pattern\n\nThis gives structure to everything else.\n\n---\n\n## **Step 2 — Draft the Topic Maps integration**\n\nProduce:\n\n* GT Book page: *“Topic Maps in GT”*\n* GT Book page: *“Roadmap Visualizations”*\n* Short guideline page: *“How to navigate & query roadmaps”*\n\nThese three unlock many other dependencies.\n\n---\n\n## **Step 3 — Generate a Scenery from the LU1 tree**\n\nOnce LU1 has its structure written down (even as bullet points), I can generate:\n\n* A Scenery definition\n* An interactive Scenery visualization\n* Derived roadmap navigation pages\n\nThis solves the “beginner orientation” problem.\n\n---\n\n## **Step 4 — Write the Accordion pattern page**\n\nVery small effort, high value.\nInclude:\n\n* Intent\n* Problem\n* Forces\n* Solution\n* Examples (Inspector + code + extraction)\n* Side road links (language workbench, Mondrian)\n\n---\n\n## **Step 5 — Produce the Wardley Map (first draft)**\n\nYou provide:\n\n* A list of components and user needs (which you already wrote)\n  I produce:\n* Wardley Map diagram\n* GT Newcomer Value Chain description\n* Explanation how GT fits the evolution model\n\nMinimal effort for a high clarity payoff.\n\n---\n\n## **Step 6 — Start with one low-priority topic**\n\nPick the one with best signal/noise:\n\n→ I suggest **Mondrian tutorial**, because it ties to Sceneries, Topic Maps, roadmaps, and code exploration.\n\n---\n\n# ✔ Summary of Immediate Next Steps (short)\n\n1. **Define LU1 as a tree of pages** (I can help generate the structure).\n2. **Draft Topic Maps + Roadmaps pages**.\n3. **Generate a Scenery for LU1**.\n4. **Write the Accordion pattern page**.\n5. **Create the Wardley Map for GT newcomers**.\n\nThis will give you:\n\n* Structure\n* Navigation\n* Orientation\n* Patterns\n* A consistent curriculum spine\n\nEverything else can attach to these five steps.\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can now:\n\n### → generate the LU1 tree\n\n### → generate Topic Maps page drafts\n\n### → generate Scenery definition\n\n### → generate Wardley map\n\n### → generate Accordion pattern page\n\nJust say **“Start with LU1 tree”** or **“Start with Topic Maps pages”**, or specify the item.\n"
